docs.abstract: A lawyer for Travis McMichael is the first on the defense side to to argue that when Ahmaud Arbery was killed, his client was trying to make a citizen’s arrest permitted under state law.

docs.lead_paragraph: Robert Rubin, a lawyer for Travis McMichael, became the first defense lawyer for any of the three men accused of murdering Ahmaud Arbery to argue that his client was trying to make a citizen’s arrest permitted under state law.

headline.main: The defense cites a citizen’s arrest law that has been largely repealed.

docs.lead_paragraph: In her closing argument, Linda Dunikoski, the lead prosecutor in the trial of the three men charged with the murder of Ahmaud Arbery, said that the defendants had no justification to pursue Mr. Arbery or to claim they were performing a citizen’s arrest, because they did not have any knowledge that Mr. Arbery had committed a crime that day — they merely assumed that he had.

headline.main: The men pursued Arbery because ‘he was a Black man running down the street,’ the prosecutor says in summation.

docs.abstract: Travis McMichael, who has pleaded not guilty to murder charges, took the stand in his own defense on Wednesday.
docs.snippet: Travis McMichael, who has pleaded not guilty to murder charges, took the stand in his own defense on Wednesday.
docs.lead_paragraph: Travis McMichael, the man who shot Ahmaud Arbery to death after chasing him through a suburban Georgia neighborhood, testified in his own defense on Wednesday, arguing that pointing his gun at Mr. Arbery was an attempt to “de-escalate” the situation, a tactic he said he had learned during use-of-force training while serving in the U.S. Coast Guard.

docs.lead_paragraph: ATLANTA — Lawyers for the three white Georgia men on trial for the murder of Ahmaud Arbery, a 25-year-old Black man, tried unsuccessfully on Monday to convince a judge to declare a mistrial, with one of the lawyers reiterating his argument that prominent Black pastors should not be allowed in the courtroom because they unfairly influence the jury.

headline.main: Judge Rejects Call for Mistrial in Case Against Men Accused of Killing Arbery
headline.print_headline: Judge Rebuffs Call for Mistrial in Arbery Case

docs.abstract: A reader’s family members say they won’t come to New York City after seeing footage of disorderly protests.
docs.snippet: A reader’s family members say they won’t come to New York City after seeing footage of disorderly protests.
docs.lead_paragraph: For 10 years, I have hosted Thanksgiving for my extended family. My brother and his family always join us. This year, my wife and I were excited to welcome everyone to our new apartment in Manhattan. But my brother dismissed the idea: He said his family, including his wife and teenage daughters, are afraid to go to any city after the sweeping protests following the murder of George Floyd. I am annoyed that they’re placing more faith in their slanted newsfeeds, which amplified footage of disorderly demonstrators, than in our accounts of people marching passionately but peacefully in our neighborhood. We could always host at our small cottage in the country, but it would be cramped. Thoughts?

headline.main: Should My Brother’s Bias Dictate Our Thanksgiving Plans?

docs.lead_paragraph: The three men who were convicted on Wednesday of murdering Ahmaud Arbery must be sentenced to life in prison, according to Georgia law, and a judge will decide whether they can be considered for parole beginning in 30 years or if they instead must die in prison.

headline.main: A judge will decide if the men convicted of murdering Ahmaud Arbery ever get a chance at parole.
